{
    "level": "A1–B1",
    "intro": "Start with <strong>word roles</strong>, the simple sentence, the <strong>Verb to Be</strong> subsection, and basic <strong>word order</strong>.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Parts of Speech",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "First, see what role a word has in a sentence.",
            "example": "noun, verb, adjective, adverb"
        },
        {
            "label": "Sentence Basics",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "Then learn the simple sentence pattern and the core sentence types.",
            "example": "Subject + Verb + Object"
        },
        {
            "label": "Verb to Be + Word Order",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "After that, move to <strong>Verb to Be</strong> and <strong>Word Order</strong> to build natural A1 sentences.",
            "example": "I am ready. / Are they here? / She often works at home."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Starter topics",
    "intro": "These topics give you a practical A1–A2 starting point for grammar.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Parts of Speech",
            "title": "Parts of speech",
            "subtitle": "Nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, and other word roles."
        },
        {
            "label": "Sentence Structure",
            "title": "Sentence structure",
            "subtitle": "The simple sentence model and the basic SVO pattern."
        },
        {
            "label": "Sentence Types",
            "title": "Sentence types",
            "subtitle": "Statements, questions, negatives, and imperatives."
        },
        {
            "label": "Imperatives",
            "title": "Imperatives",
            "subtitle": "Short commands, requests, and instructions."
        },
        {
            "label": "Conjunctions",
            "title": "Conjunctions",
            "subtitle": "and, but, or, because, so in simple links."
        },
        {
            "label": "Word Order",
            "title": "Word order",
            "subtitle": "A focused subsection on sentence order."
        },
        {
            "label": "Verb to Be",
            "title": "Verb to Be",
            "subtitle": "am, is, are, negatives, questions, and there is / there are."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. A useful path",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Foundation",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "Start with <strong>Parts of Speech</strong> and <strong>Sentence Structure</strong> so you can see word roles and the frame of a simple sentence.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The student reads a book.",
                    "ua": "Subject + verb + object."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Core models",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "Then take <strong>Sentence Types</strong>, <strong>Imperatives</strong>, and <strong>Conjunctions</strong> to build short working sentence patterns.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Open the window. / I was tired, so I stayed home.",
                    "ua": "Commands, questions, negatives, and simple links."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Verb to Be + Word Order",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "After that, move to <strong>Verb to Be</strong> and <strong>Word Order</strong> so your first sentences sound natural.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I am ready. / Are they at school? / She often works at home.",
                    "ua": "To be forms, simple questions, and natural word order."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. In short",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Parts of Speech</strong> shows what a word does in a sentence.",
        "<strong>Sentence Structure</strong> and <strong>Sentence Types</strong> give you the core A1 sentence models.",
        "<strong>Imperatives</strong> and <strong>Conjunctions</strong> add commands, requests, and simple links.",
        "<strong>Word Order</strong> helps you place words in natural English order.",
        "<strong>Verb to Be</strong> covers the starter forms <strong>am / is / are</strong>, questions, and <strong>there is / there are</strong>."
    ]
}
